---
import "../styles/main.css"
import Nav from "../components/Nav.astro"
import Footer from "../components/Footer.astro"
import ThemeInit from "../components/ThemeInit.astro"
---
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en" class="scroll-smooth">
<head><meta charset="UTF-8" /><ThemeInit /><meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
<title>Learn Japanese with Flashcards - Free App with Furigana & TTS</title>
<meta name="description" content="Learn Japanese with flashcards featuring furigana, TTS pronunciation, and spaced repetition. Free app with JLPT N5 vocabulary deck. No account required." />
<link rel="canonical" href="https://fluentcards.org/learn-japanese/" />
<meta property="og:title" content="Learn Japanese with Flashcards - Free App with Furigana" />
<meta property="og:description" content="Free Japanese flashcard app with furigana, TTS pronunciation, and spaced repetition." />
<meta property="og:url" content="https://fluentcards.org/learn-japanese/" />
<meta name="twitter:card" content="summary_large_image" />
<script type="application/ld+json">{ "@context": "https://schema.org", "@type": "WebPage", "name": "Learn Japanese with Flashcards", "url": "https://fluentcards.org/learn-japanese/" }</script>
<script async src="https://pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/js/adsbygoogle.js?client=ca-pub-4482389932723468" crossorigin="anonymous"></script>
</head>
<body class="font-sans text-slate-700 bg-white dark:bg-surface-dark dark:text-slate-400 antialiased overflow-x-hidden transition-colors duration-300">
<Nav currentPath="/learn-japanese/" />
<main class="pt-32 pb-16 px-6">
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto text-center reveal-up">
    <h1 class="text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-slate-900 dark:text-slate-100 leading-tight">Learn Japanese with Flashcards</h1>
    <p class="mt-4 text-lg text-slate-500 max-w-2xl mx-auto">Master Japanese vocabulary with flashcards that have built-in furigana, native TTS pronunciation, and smart spaced repetition. Free to use, no account needed.</p>
    <a href="/app/" class="mt-8 inline-flex items-center gap-2 bg-primary text-white px-8 py-3.5 rounded-xl font-bold shadow-lg shadow-primary/25 hover:shadow-xl transition-all">Start Learning Japanese Free</a>
  </div>

  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto mt-16 space-y-8">
    <div class="p-6 bg-white dark:bg-surface-card rounded-xl border border-slate-200 dark:border-slate-700 reveal-up">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-800 dark:text-slate-200 mb-3">Built-in Furigana Support</h2>
      <p class="text-slate-500 leading-relaxed">FluentCards has automatic furigana rendering for Japanese text. When you create flashcards using the kanji[furigana] format, the readings appear as small ruby text above each kanji. This means you can practice reading kanji while having instant access to correct pronunciations. As your reading ability improves, you can gradually rely less on furigana by using cards that show kanji without readings on the front. This progressive approach mirrors how native speakers develop kanji recognition through repeated exposure.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="p-6 bg-white dark:bg-surface-card rounded-xl border border-slate-200 dark:border-slate-700 reveal-up delay-1">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-800 dark:text-slate-200 mb-3">Native TTS Pronunciation</h2>
      <p class="text-slate-500 leading-relaxed">Every flashcard can speak Japanese text aloud using high-quality Microsoft Edge TTS. This is invaluable for learners because Japanese pronunciation requires correct pitch accent that is difficult to learn from text alone. You can adjust the speech rate from slow to natural speed, making it suitable for both beginners and advanced learners. Use the TTS feature to hear vocabulary words, example sentences, and full phrases pronounced correctly by a native-quality voice.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="p-6 bg-white dark:bg-surface-card rounded-xl border border-slate-200 dark:border-slate-700 reveal-up delay-2">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-800 dark:text-slate-200 mb-3">JLPT N5 Vocabulary Deck</h2>
      <p class="text-slate-500 leading-relaxed">Getting started is easy with our pre-built JLPT N5 vocabulary deck containing 40 essential words with kanji, furigana readings, and English translations. The deck covers the most common beginner vocabulary including greetings, numbers, verbs, adjectives, and everyday nouns. Clone the deck instantly and start studying with full TTS audio and spaced repetition scheduling. As you progress, you can create additional decks for JLPT N4 through N1 vocabulary using word lists from textbooks and exam preparation materials.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="p-6 bg-white dark:bg-surface-card rounded-xl border border-slate-200 dark:border-slate-700 reveal-up delay-3">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-800 dark:text-slate-200 mb-3">Why Flashcards Work for Japanese</h2>
      <p class="text-slate-500 leading-relaxed">Japanese requires memorizing thousands of items: kanji characters, vocabulary words, and grammar patterns. Flashcards with spaced repetition are the most efficient way to build and maintain this knowledge. The FSRS algorithm schedules each card at the optimal interval for your memory, so you spend less time reviewing and retain more. Unlike traditional methods where you review everything at fixed intervals, spaced repetition focuses your time on the words you find hardest while skipping reviews for words you already know well.</p>
      <p class="text-slate-500 leading-relaxed mt-3">For the best results, combine your flashcard study with real-world Japanese exposure. Read manga or graded readers, watch Japanese shows with subtitles, and practice speaking with language partners. Each new word you encounter reinforces the flashcards you are studying, creating a powerful cycle of acquisition and retention.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="p-6 bg-white dark:bg-surface-card rounded-xl border border-slate-200 dark:border-slate-700 reveal-up delay-3">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-800 dark:text-slate-200 mb-3">Building a Daily Study Routine</h2>
      <p class="text-slate-500 leading-relaxed">Consistency matters more than intensity. A daily routine of 15 to 20 minutes of flashcard review can yield faster progress than occasional multi-hour sessions. Start each session by reviewing due cards in FluentCards, then add 5 to 10 new vocabulary items. Use the furigana feature to learn correct readings from the beginning, and enable TTS audio to train your listening comprehension. The streak tracker helps maintain momentum by showing your consecutive study days.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="text-center mt-12 reveal-up">
    <a href="/blog/japanese-flashcard-study-guide/" class="text-sm font-semibold text-primary hover:text-primary-hover">Read our complete Japanese flashcard study guide &rarr;</a>
  </div>

<h2>Getting Started with Japanese</h2>
<p>FluentCards makes it easy to start learning Japanese. When you open the app, you can immediately access the JLPT N5 Vocabulary starter deck with 40 essential vocabulary words. Each card includes the Japanese word, English translation, and TTS audio. The FSRS spaced repetition algorithm automatically schedules your reviews for maximum efficiency. Words you find difficult appear more frequently, while words you know fade into the background.</p>
<h2>Pronunciation and Listening</h2>
<p>FluentCards includes built-in TTS pronunciation that lets you hear each Japanese word spoken naturally. Listen and repeat aloud to practice your pronunciation. Adjust the speech rate from slow to natural speed. Combine flashcard study with real-world exposure to Japanese through podcasts, videos, and conversations for the fastest results.</p>
<h2>Building Your Vocabulary</h2>
<p>Study 15 to 20 minutes daily. Review all due cards and add 5 to 10 new words. At this pace you can learn over 1,000 words in three months. The streak tracker helps maintain momentum, and the FSRS algorithm ensures retention through optimally scheduled reviews.</p>

<p>JLPT N5 starter deck gives you 40 essential Japanese words with English translations and TTS audio. studying Japanese with kanji and furigana requires tools that support the unique writing system. FluentCards provides all the tools you need to build Japanese vocabulary efficiently through spaced repetition, active recall, and consistent daily practice. The FSRS algorithm adapts to your memory and schedules reviews at optimal intervals. Start with the starter deck and expand with your own cards as you encounter new words in your studies. Whether you are learning for travel, work, or personal enrichment, FluentCards helps you make steady progress toward your Japanese goals.</p><p>Consistent daily practice is the key to language learning success. Study for 15 to 20 minutes each day, complete all due reviews, and add 5 to 10 new vocabulary items. The streak tracker keeps you motivated, and the progress statistics show your improvements over time. With FluentCards, you have a complete language learning system that works on any device, anywhere, without requiring an account or subscription.</p><p>The combination of flashcards, TTS pronunciation, and spaced repetition creates a powerful learning environment that addresses reading comprehension, listening comprehension, and speaking ability simultaneously. By integrating these elements into a single seamless application, FluentCards helps you learn Japanese more efficiently than traditional methods allow.</p>
<p>FluentCards Japanese language support includes automatic furigana rendering for kanji characters, which is essential for reading development. When you type text using the bracket notation, the app displays the kana readings above each kanji. This feature bridges the gap between recognizing a character and knowing its pronunciation, accelerating your reading ability significantly. The JLPT N5 deck provides a solid foundation of 40 essential words, and as you progress, you can create additional decks for N4 through N1 vocabulary using official word lists and your own study materials.</p><p>Japanese study requires consistent daily practice because the writing system and grammar are fundamentally different from English. Even a short 15-minute daily session produces better results than occasional intensive study. The FluentCards streak tracker helps you maintain consistency, and the progress statistics show your improvements over time. With dedication and the right tools, achieving Japanese reading and conversational fluency is an attainable goal for any motivated learner.</p>
</main>
<Footer />
<script>const o=new IntersectionObserver(e=>{e.forEach(e=>{e.isIntersecting&&e.target.classList.add("visible")})},{threshold:.08});document.querySelectorAll(".reveal-up").forEach(e=>o.observe(e));</script>
</body>
</html>
